				\begin{document}$$\Vert v\Vert$$\end{document} is the flow velocity in the principle direction, the subscript L refers the longitudinal direction and the subscript T refers the transverse direction. The dispersivity of the porous medium depends on its tortuosity and heterogeneity. However, the experimental measured values vary by several orders of magnitude. As the process is strongly depending on the considered scale, laboratory measurements cannot be directly transferred to reservoir scale (Tek 1989). Tracer tests, which have been performed on reservoir scale, have shown that the longitudinal dispersivity is between 1 and 100 m (Tek 1989; Carriere et al. 1985; Laille et al. 1986). The transverse dispersivity is usually one or two orders smaller. Assuming flow velocities of several meters per day, which are common in gas storages, the longitudinal mechanical dispersion coefficient will be around 5×10-4\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
